{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/palliative-care-cough/prescribing-information/pholcodine-linctus-bp/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"b13d017f-af1d-5851-8c0e-967352e91bde","slug":"pholcodine-linctus-bp","fullItemName":"Pholcodine linctus BP","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field c92c144e-1248-43b8-a5d7-1dbf56c49d82 --><h2>Pholcodine linctus BP</h2><!-- end field c92c144e-1248-43b8-a5d7-1dbf56c49d82 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 85160c1b-beff-45a2-bdb6-41cf90678155 --><!-- begin field 63f4cfa1-c6ab-4457-8e02-0fdb7f7b4039 --><ul><li>If the person is already taking a strong opioid such as morphine, do not try a weak opioid such as pholcodine. Instead an 'as required' dose of morphine solution should be used to relieve cough.</li><li>Pholcodine Linctus BP 5 to 10 mg may be taken three to four times a day for symptomatic relief of unproductive coughs. Sugar-free brands are available where preferred, and for people with diabetes.</li><li>The adverse effects usually associated with opioids (e.g. constipation) are rarely reported, as pholcodine is such a weak opioid. However, it has mild sedative properties and so people should be warned to avoid activities where drowsiness may be detrimental.</li><li>If pholcodine (or codeine) is ineffective, switch to morphine solution 5 mg to 10 mg every 4 hours and 'as required'. For people who are opioid naive, use a dose of 2.5 to 5 mg every 4 hours.</li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-cough/references/\">ABPI Medicines Compendium, 2015a</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/palliative-care-cough/references/\">BNF 72, 2016</a>]  </p><!-- end field 63f4cfa1-c6ab-4457-8e02-0fdb7f7b4039 --><!-- end item 85160c1b-beff-45a2-bdb6-41cf90678155 -->","topic":{"id":"d321ef5c-4612-5a6b-aafc-a656ec8fb1e6","topicId":"561865b5-2a09-480f-ae63-78